&lt;pre&gt;*Contact emails*
&lt;a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="d3b7b1b2fdfdfd93b0bba1bcbebaa6befdbca1b4"&gt;[email&#160;protected]&lt;/a&gt;

*Explainer*
&lt;a  rel="nofollow" href="https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/blob/main/css-conditional-5/named-feature-explainer.md"&gt;https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/blob/main/css-conditional-5/named-feature-explainer.md&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;pre&gt;

*Specification*
&lt;a  rel="nofollow" href="https://drafts.csswg.org/css-conditional-5/#typedef-supports-named-feature-fn"&gt;https://drafts.csswg.org/css-conditional-5/#typedef-supports-named-feature-fn&lt;/a&gt;

*Summary*
The named-feature() function allows CSS @supports rules to query for a
small set of specific named features that are not possible to test for
using other @supports mechanisms but which are considered highly valuable
to test for.

*Blink component*
Blink&gt;CSS
&lt;&lt;a  rel="nofollow" href="https://issues.chromium.org/issues?q=customfield1222907:%22Blink%3ECSS%22"&gt;https://issues.chromium.org/issues?q=customfield1222907:%22Blink%3ECSS%22&lt;/a&gt;&gt;

*Web Feature ID*
Missing feature
&lt;&lt;a  rel="nofollow" href="https://github.com/web-platform-dx/web-features/issues/3697"&gt;https://github.com/web-platform-dx/web-features/issues/3697&lt;/a&gt;&gt;

*Motivation*
Sometimes we add new features to CSS where two things are simultaneously
true: first, that CSS authors see high value in writing conditional styles
for whether the feature is supported using @supports, and second, that the
existing mechanisms in @supports don't provide a useful way to test for the
feature. This provides a way for us to give names to a small number of
high-value features so that CSS authors can test for them in their style
sheets.

*Initial public proposal*
&lt;a  rel="nofollow" href="https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/3559#issuecomment-1868169502"&gt;https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/3559#issuecomment-1868169502&lt;/a&gt;

